-- Astarta, Bank Zachodni, Orbis, PGE, Polimex: Central Europe Stock Preview
-- Marta Waldoch
-- 2010-07-21T06:24:04Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/astarta-bank-zachodni-orbis-pge-polimex-central-europe-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in central European
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names.
Share prices are from the last close.  
 Poland’s  WIG20 Index  fell 0.9 percent, the Czech  PX Index 
dropped 0.4 percent and Hungary’s  BUX Index  added 0.5 percent.  
 Astarta Holding NV  (AST PW): Ukraine’s biggest producer of
refined sugar, which trades in Warsaw, plans to increase output
42 percent after prices doubled last year, Chief Executive
Officer  Viktor Ivanchyk  said. Astarta was unchanged at 59 zloty.  
 Bank Zachodni WBK SA  (BZW PW): Intesa Sanpaolo SpA of Italy
is on the shortlist to buy a stake in Poland’s Bank Zachodni WBK
SA from Allied Irish Banks Plc, Dziennik reported, without
citing anyone. Zachodni dropped 2.3 percent to 192 zloty.  
 New World Resources NV  (NWR CP): The company said it
expects average coking coal prices to rise 17 percent in the
third quarter compared to the April-June period. NWR was
unchanged at 218 koruna.  
 Orbis SA  (ORB PW): Poland’s biggest hotel chain estimates
its revenue totaled 399 million zloty in the first half of this
year, it said in a preliminary statement. The shares declined
1.6 percent to 36.4 zloty.  
 PGE SA  (PGE PW): Poland’s largest electricity producer
plans to sell “almost” all of its production on power
exchanges starting in 2011, Rzeczpospolita reported, citing
Chief Executive Officer  Tomasz Zadroga . PGE fell 0.7 percent to
21.15 zloty.  
 Polimex-Mostostal SA  (PXM PW): A group including Poland’s
largest builder and  Doprastav AS  (DOP SK) of Slovakia signed a
788.1 million-zloty ($247.2 million) contract to build a section
of a highway in southern Poland, Polimex said in a statement.
Polimex rose 0.7 percent to 4.57 zloty.  
